annotation.TEXT: That was cool.
Hitting both turn blocks there is a good idea, because it causes the saw to fall through them. (The saw won't fall through if you only hit one turn block, and that could complicate things.)
That RVF up there was starting to embed itself into the wall for some reason.
Whoa, what the heck?! That was weird. Okay, as a "science", I'm going to try that again.
Hmm... If it weren't for the random level, there would've been a 4-way tie for 2nd (or a 5-way tie if the random level chose 8-2)!
Now, what's to the right? Is there anything at all? Or is there just going to be EVW-like emptiness over here?
Alright, that's enough of that. So, 6-5 is Noisy Sea... What does it mean by "Noisy"?
And, that opens up the path to 6-6 from the north. Now, 9-6 got second place this time, so let's head to New Impossible Request "Seamless Ceiling of Kinkaku-ji"... Oh, wait. That's a different game.

This part is more dangerous than it may look at first. If you go above that rope, you'll be crushed between it and the off screen ceiling (though I imagine that you could pass through the rope from above by swimming while holding down as the rope's ascending to escape).
Nothing but coins in those blocks.
I'm low on time, so I'll turn back when the timer hits 30.
Getting past these saws might be tricky, but maybe I can get Mr. Wizard to widen one of the gaps so that the saws fall through?
This update fixed the "Wizard's" typo in 6-3's level name, but I'm not sure what else it changed, if anything. If this update did change other things, let me know!
There doesn't appear to be a way to reach that Chuck, so he's going to be whistling all day until I get far enough away.
Argh! And I'm going to need a shell to get through here!
So, why are there a few screens of emptiness beyond the goal? Maybe the screen was actually supposed to stop scrolling where that cutoff in the land is?
And with that, every world 9 level has been cleared! ...Huh, what's with that little graphical glitch down there?
Oh, and unlike in Chaos CompleXX, there's no reaching those moons with a cape-flying corner clip!
Yeah, let's try to hang onto this shell. Also, it's neat how I can stop it by breaking a nearby block.
MOOOOOONNNSSS!!!!! MOONY-MOONY-MOONS!!!
NOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOO!!!!!!!!
And that's it. Wow, only 4 levels to pick from this time. I remember when there were 14 at one time! Well, place your votes for which level(s) you want me to play next time! To be continued...
I doubt there was any way to keep that Chuck from whistling.
In addition, there appear to be pipes on a smashing layer 2. That would certainly add to the noisiness. Still, I gotta check every pipe...
Whoa. I saw the shell start to shake, because it's still occupied. I'd better do something about that occupant...
Goal tape average so far: 3244 / 82 = 39.561 stars each.
Perfect!
Now, in this level, there are loads and loads of these fragile blocks, and they automatically bounce you upwards as you break them. Keep this in mind, as it can mess with your ability to dodge stuff.

Yeah, I just ended up below the floor there. That's weird how it does that. I guess swimming upwards at a slower rate than a rising layer 2 can do that, but I imagine that it could also kill me easily if I'm careless.
Alright! That was definitely tricky!
You can lessen the upward bounce effect by holding down, but you're still going to bounce upwards at least a little bit when you break a block (unless you're already touching a ceiling).
Hello, and welcome back to Super Marina World! Now, let's see what the voters have decided this time...
Oh, yeah. I think this shell is in the perfect sprite slot for dealing with any Thwomps since it came from a block!
Oh, that's odd. When I'm rubbing my head against a ceiling while holding an item, I pass through the fragile blocks just below that ceiling without breaking them. Weird...
Whoops, I meant to dodge to the right of the Thwomp there, but the note block sent me to the left instead. At least I still dodged it!
There's midpoint, with a whistling Chuck right below what I assume is the midpoint entrance pipe, so that Chuck's placement makes perfect sense!
Whoa! I'm glad I followed the coins down here! Okay, so I'm at the goal, but... Can I swim under it?
Oh, nice. I nailed Mr. Wizard as well!
And, also, there's cutoff down here. Whoops!
Now, let's run some laps between 6-3 and 6-4...
Oh, sure. It starts letting me through just as I decide to go for that wider gap on the right.
Yeah, you'd have to do some extra mace dodging if you took the left route back there.
Okay, I'm going to need Mr. Wizard's help here.
Ha! That was neat. Also, I now have another Thwomp-killing shell to use!
Or, I'll turn back a few seconds before that, because the screen stopped scrolling there.
I'm still sick of that "annotation not disappearing" glitch, and I'm going to keep complaining about it from time to time...
Argh! How'd I screw that up? (I even saw Luica spin around after shrinking, so I definitely started cape spinning before that RVF hit me, but the cape spin didn't thwack it in time.)
With Mr. Wizard's help, of course! ...Assuming the note blocks will let me squeeze into this gap...
D'oh! Lost the shell...
Darn it. That shell is also useless for killing this Thwomp. I may have to just try to dodge this Thwomp, which will be tricky with Mr. Wizard also harassing me...

Whoa, that RVF appeared rather suddenly. Okay, now I've definitely got to start being careful around these pipes... Also, I've decided that I'm not going to bother checking every pipe in this level, but if I miss any bonus rooms as a result, let me know!
Doubled back since I didn't like the mace's position there.
What the...? Another oddity? I've seen this before, actually, where fireballs can go through parts of solid layer 2 objects for some reason. Any idea why that happens?
Zwee! I assume that pipe on the left is the midpoint entrance.
BGM: 1943 (NES) - Mission Theme 2
Be mindful of the note blocks as well. They're all of the "bounce on all sides" variety and you could end up bouncing crazily about if you're not careful.
Alright, so 6-5 it is! Oh, I guess I should mention that I'm now playing the updated version of this hack that I mentioned last time.
Now, how do I open this ? block on the left?
Cool, another flower, which I can reach while super this time! Also, will this shell work on the Thwomps as well?
I love this shell.
Over here, you want to go up the right side, which will be more convenient for you later. And of course, try to limit the number of note blocks you bounce off of.
Uh, oh. There's an impassable row of note blocks up ahead. How will I ever get through them?
Aww... I was hoping to get a double kill there.

Oh! The goal at the top here is now a goal sphere! It was a regular goal post when raocow played this level, but this is probably better, because if you pass 100 bonus stars from hitting a goal in a vertical level, the bonus game won't trigger for some reason (which was the case for raocow).
9-6 is actually called "Destructiocean", which looks like a clever merging of the words "Destruction" and "Ocean".
I'm pretty sure you need to be holding a shell here in order to swim fast enough to get through these bones before they crush you.
First of all, there's a couple of clapping Chucks, which I'll beat up for the heck of it.
Farfignewton. Whatever. There's a replacement flower right there.
By using this shell that I get from the right ? block, of course!
5-life combo! But... Maybe I shouldn't have slowed down for some of those kills. Now I've gotta do some dodging.
Oh, man. Am I getting back into that habit of hearing the "Hurry up!" warning in every episode again?
This part with the two Thwimps and the mace is tough. Let's see if I can avoid getting hit here...
...Whoa! And it looks like this would be a good place to do some Thwomp-killing!
Oh, there's a whistling Chuck right at the start that wakes up all of the Rip Van Fish in the level. Yeah, that would qualify as noisy!
I wonder why there's another whistling Chuck here. The first one's whistling effect will never go away unless I leave the level or go into another sublevel. Maybe it's here to add to the noisiness.
This level also contains plenty of castle-based obstacles, such as maces, Thwimps, and saws. Some are really tricky to avoid.

Wow, talk about cutting it close. I'm glad the screen stopped scrolling when it did over there. (Although, I probably still would've made it back in time if it kept going and I turned back at 30 seconds left, but I might've been forced to hit the goal for a low bonus star amount.)

Yes, just barely, but... Augh! I can't collect the flower it revealed while I'm super! That stinks! (Maybe it should be changed to give a feather instead, or be made to act like a yellow ! block and always give a mushroom regardless of the player's status.)
D'oh! Why did the shell fail there? ...Oh, right. I took it through a pipe, which changed its sprite slot to I think 0 (from I think the 11 it started at), which makes it useless for Thwomp-killing.
Oh, man. Can I reach that ? block (that I think has a power up I could use) without getting maced?
Oh, wow. What a lucky break!
Yes I can, and there's stuff over here!
Well, that little graphical glitch is gone now.

Well, whatever. I'm not going to try breaking the level by swimming under the floor like that. Besides, I'd still have to deal with layer 2 objects down there, which could be impossible depending on how they're placed.
Well, let's see which levels there are to choose from now like usual...

More slamming layer 2, but it looks like it's using a different slamming effect now. (It's now using the slamming effect found in #6 Wendy's Castle and Valley Fortress in the original game, while the previous area used the slamming effect found in door #5 of Bowser's castle (Front Door).)
Those coins were probably not really worth the risk, but whatever.
Bonus room music? Invincibility? Yeah, now we're at the fun part of the level! However, I am kind of low on time.
Four shells to choose from, eh? I'll pick green since I'm using the green character. (Although, I could've made this decision with a tie-breaker round here... Oh, well.)
